{"title_page": "American Revolutionary Party", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=American Revolutionary Party|timestamp=20200410151422|year=2020|month=April|day=10|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=American Revolutionary Party|date=10 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n<!-- Do not remove this line! -->{{Infobox political party\n| name = American Revolutionary Party\n| seats2_title = [[United States House of Representatives|Seats in the House]]\n| leader2_name = Steven Amonett\n| seats8_title = [[Territories of the United States|Territorial Lower Chamber Seats]]\n| seats8 = <!--Don't change numbers, until terms begin--> {{composition bar|0|91|hex={{Republican Party (US)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats7_title = [[Territories of the United States|Territorial Upper Chamber Seats]]\n| seats7 = <!--Don't change numbers, until terms begin--> {{composition bar|0|97|hex={{Republican Party (US)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats6_title = [[Governor (United States)|Territorial Governorships]]\n| seats6 = <!--Don't change numbers, until terms begin--> {{composition bar|0|6|hex={{Republican Party (US)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats5_title = [[State legislature (United States)|State Lower Chamber Seats]]\n| seats5 = <!--Don't change numbers, until terms begin--> {{composition bar|0|5411|hex={{Republican Party (US)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats4_title = [[State legislature (United States)|State Upper Chamber Seats]]\n| seats4 = <!--Don't change numbers, until terms begin--> {{composition bar|0|1972|hex={{Republican Party (US)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats3_title = [[Governor (United States)|State Governorships]]\n| seats3 = <!--Don't change numbers, until terms begin--> {{composition bar|0|50|hex={{Republican Party (US)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats2 = <!--Don't change numbers, until terms begin--> {{composition bar|0|435|hex={{Republican Party (US)/meta/color}}}}\n| logo = ARP Logo.png\n| seats1_title = [[United States Senate|Seats in the Senate]]\n| seats1 = <!--Don't change numbers, until terms begin--> {{composition bar|0|100|hex={{Republican Party (US)/meta/color}}}}\n| membership_year = 2020\n| membership = {{increase}} 22\n| abbreviation = ARP\n| website = {{url|sites.google.com/view/americanrevolutionaryparty}}\n| leader1_title = General Secretary\n| leader1_name = Garrett Roches\n| position = [[Far-left]]\n| foundation = September 6, 2019; 7 months ago\n| ideology = [[Communism]]<br>\nLeft Unity\n| colors = {{colour box|{{Party for Socialism and Liberation/meta/color}}}} [[Red]]\n| colorcode = {{Party for Socialism and Liberation/meta/color}}\n| leader2_title = Second Secretary\n| country = United States\n| wing1 = [[United States]]\n| wing1_title = Area Served\n}}\n\nThe '''American Revolutionary Party'''; abbreviated as the ARP is a [[Far-left politics|far-left]] [[political party]] in the [[United States|United States of America]]. The party describes itself as a left-unity party with a diverse range of leftists.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/view/americanrevolutionaryparty/about-us/overview|title=American Revolutionary Party - Overview|website=sites.google.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> While the party is based in the United States, it has members from foreign nations as well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/view/americanrevolutionaryparty/about-us/meet-our-leadership|title=American Revolutionary Party - Meet Our Leadership|website=sites.google.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Formation of the Party ===\n{{Communist parties}}\nOn September 6, 2019, the former Chairman of the American Revolutionary Party, Elai Devar, founded the American Revolutionary Party. By January of 2020, the party reportedly had over fifty active members.\n\n=== February Reforms ===\nAfter a failed merger with another political party, former Chairman Elai Devar resigned<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/view/americanrevolutionaryparty/about-us/history-of-the-party|title=American Revolutionary Party - History of the Party|website=sites.google.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> and reforms were made within the party. The reforms included a change in leadership, a change in leadership structure, a change in the general party structure, and adopting a new constitution. A new leader was officially appointed on March 3, 2020.<ref name=\"auto2\" />\n\n{{American socialism}}\n\n== Ideology ==\nThe party's ideology is [[communism]] and left unity. The ARP seeks to unite all leftists to create an effective [[proletarian revolution]]. Since its founding, the American Revolutionary Party has also been [[Anti-fascism|anti-fascist]]; [[Anti-capitalism|anti-capitalist]], believing that capitalism will \"destruct itself\";<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B67IC48gZHk/|title=American Revolutionary Party\u2019s Instagram post: \u201cWhy capitalism will destruct itself. -An educational post by the ARP- Capitalism, for a long time, has dominated the course of human\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> and [[Anti-imperialism|anti-imperialist]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B3lY87Zgl6D/|title=American Revolutionary Party on Instagram: \u201cPeople before persecution, people before profit, and people before anything else. Socialism for the people, socialism by the people, and\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> The ARP advocates for [[LGBTQ rights|LGBTQ+ rights]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B8969khgE1H/|title=American Revolutionary Party on Instagram: \u201cThe ARP is currently under a period of reorganization and restructuring. In the mean time we want to make a few posts about what we\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> [[women's rights]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B6AAICHgR1K/|title=American Revolutionary Party on Instagram: \u201cJoin the American Revolutionary Party. Make your voice heard. Together we can change the world, or suffer.\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> reforming the education system, putting an end to \"imperialist [[War|wars]],\"<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B63LFGLgywm/|title=American Revolutionary Party on Instagram: \u201cTrump has now jeopardized the peace of the world. The death of Qasem Soleimani caused by American airstrikes has done nothing but cause\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> and [[Green politics|protecting the environment]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B2x_c_8phNT/|title=American Revolutionary Party on Instagram: \u201cWe must not let capitalists continue to abuse the planet for their profit. - There is no PLANet B.\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> They are skeptical of [[Election|electoral politics]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B-vAsqmgDZB/|title=American Revolutionary Party on Instagram: \u201cThe 2020 Presidential Elections is probably the worst election in the history of the United States. Two candidates with the same policy,\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> and believe that a [[two-party system]] within a [[liberal democracy]] is an \"oppressive bureaucracy.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B69PrtKg3hn/|title=American Revolutionary Party on Instagram: \u201cThe Two Party System simply Doesn't Work -An ARP educational post- For most of America's history, there were only two parties; the\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nRegarding economics, the ARP is against [[Free-market economy|free market economy]] but hasn't explicitly stated their support for a [[Planned economy of the Soviet Union|Soviet-style planned economy]].\n\nThe ARP is supportive of [[Universal health care|free healthcare]], [[free education]], legalization of [[same-sex marriage]], adoption rights for same-sex couples, and taking aggressive action against [[Global warming|climate change]] by implementing a [[Green New Deal]].<ref name=\"auto1\" />\n\nThe ARP opposed the [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike|assassination]] of Iranian [[Major general]] [[Qasem Soleimani]], saying that the \"American airstrikes has done nothing but cause more unrest.\"<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\nThe ARP supports the [[Strikes during the 2020 coronavirus pandemic|2020 April Rent Strike]] and has demanded for the government to freeze rent due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B-LPH_rAh0-/|title=American Revolutionary Party on Instagram: \u201cThey cannot evict us all. Join in comrades, together we must fight in solidarity. #abolishrent #rentstrike2020 #notdying4wallstreet\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== Current Activities ==\nThe ARP currently has chapters in four different states: [[Kentucky]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[New York (state)|New York]], and [[Texas]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/view/americanrevolutionaryparty/chapters/kentucky|title=American Revolutionary Party - Kentucky|website=sites.google.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/view/americanrevolutionaryparty/chapters/new-york|title=American Revolutionary Party - New York|website=sites.google.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/view/americanrevolutionaryparty/chapters/pennsylvania|title=American Revolutionary Party - Pennsylvania|website=sites.google.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/view/americanrevolutionaryparty/chapters/texas|title=American Revolutionary Party - Texas|website=sites.google.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> A chapter formerly operated in the [[Midwestern United States|Midwest]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/arp_midwest_chapter/|title=Midwest- ARP (@arp_midwest_chapter) \u2022 Instagram photos and videos|website=www.instagram.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> \n\nAccording to the April Agenda of the ARP, current goals of the ARP are increasing membership, creating an education program, distributing information regarding the party, and starting a meal supply campaign.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B-f_w67AWIC/|title=American Revolutionary Party on Instagram: \u201cThis is the ARP's April Agenda! These are just some basic goals that we wish to achieve in the month of April. Make sure to stay safe\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== List of Leaders ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!\n! width=\"150\" |Name\n! width=\"150\" |Took office\n! width=\"150\" |Left office\n! width=\"150\" |Served\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" |Chairman\n|-\n|'''1'''\n|\n|'''Elai Devar'''\n|6 September 2019\n|3 Feburary 2020\n|5 Months\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!\n! width=\"150\" |Name\n! width=\"150\" |Took office\n! width=\"150\" |Left office\n! width=\"150\" |Served\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" |General Secretary\n|-\n|'''2'''\n|\n|'''Garrett Roches'''\n|3 March 2020\n|Incumbent\n|1 Month\n|}\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External Links ==\n[https://sites.google.com/view/americanrevolutionaryparty Official Website of the ARP]\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=American Revolutionary Party|timestamp=20200410151422|year=2020|month=April|day=10|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=American Revolutionary Party|date=10 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n<!-- Do not remove this line! -->{{Infobox political party\n| name = American Revolutionary Party\n| seats2_title = [[United States House of Representatives|Seats in the House]]\n| leader2_name = Steven Amonett\n| seats8_title = [[Territories of the United States|Territorial Lower Chamber Seats]]\n| seats8 = <!--Don't change numbers, until terms begin--> {{composition bar|0|91|hex={{Republican Party (US)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats7_title = [[Territories of the United States|Territorial Upper Chamber Seats]]\n| seats7 = <!--Don't change numbers, until terms begin--> {{composition bar|0|97|hex={{Republican Party (US)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats6_title = [[Governor (United States)|Territorial Governorships]]\n| seats6 = <!--Don't change numbers, until terms begin--> {{composition bar|0|6|hex={{Republican Party (US)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats5_title = [[State legislature (United States)|State Lower Chamber Seats]]\n| seats5 = <!--Don't change numbers, until terms begin--> {{composition bar|0|5411|hex={{Republican Party (US)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats4_title = [[State legislature (United States)|State Upper Chamber Seats]]\n| seats4 = <!--Don't change numbers, until terms begin--> {{composition bar|0|1972|hex={{Republican Party (US)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats3_title = [[Governor (United States)|State Governorships]]\n| seats3 = <!--Don't change numbers, until terms begin--> {{composition bar|0|50|hex={{Republican Party (US)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats2 = <!--Don't change numbers, until terms begin--> {{composition bar|0|435|hex={{Republican Party (US)/meta/color}}}}\n| logo = ARP Logo.png\n| seats1_title = [[United States Senate|Seats in the Senate]]\n| seats1 = <!--Don't change numbers, until terms begin--> {{composition bar|0|100|hex={{Republican Party (US)/meta/color}}}}\n| membership_year = 2020\n| membership = {{increase}} 22\n| abbreviation = ARP\n| website = {{url|sites.google.com/view/americanrevolutionaryparty}}\n| leader1_title = General Secretary\n| leader1_name = Garrett Roches\n| position = [[Far-left]]\n| foundation = September 6, 2019; 7 months ago\n| ideology = [[Communism]]<br>\nLeft Unity\n| colors = {{colour box|{{Party for Socialism and Liberation/meta/color}}}} [[Red]]\n| colorcode = {{Party for Socialism and Liberation/meta/color}}\n| leader2_title = Second Secretary\n| country = United States\n| wing1 = [[United States]]\n| wing1_title = Area Served\n}}\n\nThe '''American Revolutionary Party'''; abbreviated as the ARP is a [[Far-left politics|far-left]] [[political party]] in the [[United States|United States of America]]. The party describes itself as a left-unity party with a diverse range of leftists.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/view/americanrevolutionaryparty/about-us/overview|title=American Revolutionary Party - Overview|website=sites.google.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> While the party is based in the United States, it has members from foreign nations as well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/view/americanrevolutionaryparty/about-us/meet-our-leadership|title=American Revolutionary Party - Meet Our Leadership|website=sites.google.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Formation of the Party ===\n{{Communist parties}}\nOn September 6, 2019, the former Chairman of the American Revolutionary Party, Elai Devar, founded the American Revolutionary Party. By January of 2020, the party reportedly had over fifty active members.\n\n=== February Reforms ===\nAfter a failed merger with another political party, former Chairman Elai Devar resigned<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/view/americanrevolutionaryparty/about-us/history-of-the-party|title=American Revolutionary Party - History of the Party|website=sites.google.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> and reforms were made within the party. The reforms included a change in leadership, a change in leadership structure, a change in the general party structure, and adopting a new constitution. A new leader was officially appointed on March 3, 2020.<ref name=\"auto2\" />\n\n{{American socialism}}\n\n== Ideology ==\nThe party's ideology is [[communism]] and left unity. The ARP seeks to unite all leftists to create an effective [[proletarian revolution]]. Since its founding, the American Revolutionary Party has also been [[Anti-fascism|anti-fascist]]; [[Anti-capitalism|anti-capitalist]], believing that capitalism will \"destruct itself\";<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B67IC48gZHk/|title=American Revolutionary Party\u2019s Instagram post: \u201cWhy capitalism will destruct itself. -An educational post by the ARP- Capitalism, for a long time, has dominated the course of human\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> and [[Anti-imperialism|anti-imperialist]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B3lY87Zgl6D/|title=American Revolutionary Party on Instagram: \u201cPeople before persecution, people before profit, and people before anything else. Socialism for the people, socialism by the people, and\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> The ARP advocates for [[LGBTQ rights|LGBTQ+ rights]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B8969khgE1H/|title=American Revolutionary Party on Instagram: \u201cThe ARP is currently under a period of reorganization and restructuring. In the mean time we want to make a few posts about what we\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> [[women's rights]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B6AAICHgR1K/|title=American Revolutionary Party on Instagram: \u201cJoin the American Revolutionary Party. Make your voice heard. Together we can change the world, or suffer.\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> reforming the education system, putting an end to \"imperialist [[War|wars]],\"<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B63LFGLgywm/|title=American Revolutionary Party on Instagram: \u201cTrump has now jeopardized the peace of the world. The death of Qasem Soleimani caused by American airstrikes has done nothing but cause\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> and [[Green politics|protecting the environment]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B2x_c_8phNT/|title=American Revolutionary Party on Instagram: \u201cWe must not let capitalists continue to abuse the planet for their profit. - There is no PLANet B.\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> They are skeptical of [[Election|electoral politics]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B-vAsqmgDZB/|title=American Revolutionary Party on Instagram: \u201cThe 2020 Presidential Elections is probably the worst election in the history of the United States. Two candidates with the same policy,\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> and believe that a [[two-party system]] within a [[liberal democracy]] is an \"oppressive bureaucracy.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B69PrtKg3hn/|title=American Revolutionary Party on Instagram: \u201cThe Two Party System simply Doesn't Work -An ARP educational post- For most of America's history, there were only two parties; the\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nRegarding economics, the ARP is against [[Free-market economy|free market economy]] but hasn't explicitly stated their support for a [[Planned economy of the Soviet Union|Soviet-style planned economy]].\n\nThe ARP is supportive of [[Universal health care|free healthcare]], [[free education]], legalization of [[same-sex marriage]], adoption rights for same-sex couples, and taking aggressive action against [[Global warming|climate change]] by implementing a [[Green New Deal]].<ref name=\"auto1\" />\n\nThe ARP opposed the [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike|assassination]] of Iranian [[Major general]] [[Qasem Soleimani]], saying that the \"American airstrikes has done nothing but cause more unrest.\"<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\nThe ARP supports the [[Strikes during the 2020 coronavirus pandemic|2020 April Rent Strike]] and has demanded for the government to freeze rent due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B-LPH_rAh0-/|title=American Revolutionary Party on Instagram: \u201cThey cannot evict us all. Join in comrades, together we must fight in solidarity. #abolishrent #rentstrike2020 #notdying4wallstreet\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== Current Activities ==\nThe ARP currently has chapters in four different states: [[Kentucky]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[New York (state)|New York]], and [[Texas]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/view/americanrevolutionaryparty/chapters/kentucky|title=American Revolutionary Party - Kentucky|website=sites.google.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/view/americanrevolutionaryparty/chapters/new-york|title=American Revolutionary Party - New York|website=sites.google.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/view/americanrevolutionaryparty/chapters/pennsylvania|title=American Revolutionary Party - Pennsylvania|website=sites.google.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/view/americanrevolutionaryparty/chapters/texas|title=American Revolutionary Party - Texas|website=sites.google.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> A chapter formerly operated in the [[Midwestern United States|Midwest]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/arp_midwest_chapter/|title=Midwest- ARP (@arp_midwest_chapter) \u2022 Instagram photos and videos|website=www.instagram.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> \n\nAccording to the April Agenda of the ARP, current goals of the ARP are increasing membership, creating an education program, distributing information regarding the party, and starting a meal supply campaign.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B-f_w67AWIC/|title=American Revolutionary Party on Instagram: \u201cThis is the ARP's April Agenda! These are just some basic goals that we wish to achieve in the month of April. Make sure to stay safe\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== List of Leaders ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!\n! width=\"150\" |Name\n! width=\"150\" |Took office\n! width=\"150\" |Left office\n! width=\"150\" |Served\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" |Chairman\n|-\n|'''1'''\n|\n|'''Elai Devar'''\n|6 September 2019\n|3 Feburary 2020\n|5 Months\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!\n! width=\"150\" |Name\n! width=\"150\" |Took office\n! width=\"150\" |Left office\n! width=\"150\" |Served\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" |General Secretary\n|-\n|'''2'''\n|\n|'''Garrett Roches'''\n|3 March 2020\n|Incumbent\n|1 Month\n|}\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External Links ==\n[https://sites.google.com/view/americanrevolutionaryparty Official Website of the ARP]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added {{Uncategorized}} tag to article (UsingTwinkle)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Revolutionary_Party"}
{"title_page": "Surge (glacier)", "text_new": "'''Glacial surges''' are short-lived events where a [[glacier]] can advance substantially, moving at velocities up to 100 times faster than normal.  Surging glaciers cluster around a few areas. High concentrations of surging glaciers occur in [[Svalbard]], the [[Canadian Arctic islands]], [[Alaska]] and [[Iceland]]. In some glaciers, surges can occur in fairly regular cycles, with 15 to 100 or more surge events per year. In other glaciers, surging remains unpredictable.<ref>Summerfield, Michael A., 1991, ''Global Geomorphology, an introduction to the study of landforms,'' Pearson, Prentice Hall. Harlow, England</ref> In some glaciers, however, the period of stagnation and build-up between two surges typically lasts 10 to 200 years and is called the quiescent phase.<ref name=Dowdeswell>\nDowdeswell, J. A., B. Unwin, A. M. Nuttall and D. J. Wingham. 1999. Velocity structure, flow instability and mass flux on a large Arctic ice cap from satellite radar interferometry. Elsevier Science B.V.\n</ref>\nDuring this period the velocities of the glacier are significantly lower, and the glaciers can [[glacier retreat|retreat]] substantially.\n\n==Types==\n\nGlacier surges have been divided into two categories depending on the character of the surge event. Glaciers in Alaska exhibit surges with a sudden onset, an extremely high maximum flow rate (tens of meters/day) and a sudden termination, often with a discharge of stored water. These are called Alaskan-type surges and it is suspected that these surges are hydrologically controlled.<ref>Sharp, M., 1988, ''Surging glaciers: geomorphic effects,'' Progress in Physical geography, http://ppg.sagepub.com</ref>\n\nSurges in Svalbard typically exhibit different behavior. Svalbard surges are typically associated with slower onset with an acceleration phase, rising to a maximum velocity which is typically slower (up to four or five meters per day) than Alaskan surges, and a return to quiescence often taking years.<ref name=JJ>Jiskoot, H. and D. T. Juhlin, 2009, ''Surge of a small East Greenland glacier, 2001\u20132007, suggests Svalbard-type surge mechanism,'' Journal of Glaciology, Vol. 55, No. 191, pp. 567\u2013570</ref><ref>Murray, T., T. Strozzi, A. Luckman, H. Jiskoot, and P. Christakos (2003), ''Is there a single surge mechanism? Contrasts in dynamics between glacier surges in Svalbard and other regions,'' J. Geophys. Res., 108(B5), 2237, {{doi|10.1029/2002JB001906}} </ref>  Features observed during the active or surge phase include [[pothole]]s, known as lacunas<ref>Post, A. 1969, ''Distribution of surging glaciers in western North America,'' J. Glaciol., 8(53), 229-240.</ref> and medial moraines.<ref>Benn, Douglas I. and David J. A. Evans, ''Glaciers and Glaciation,'' Hodder Arnold, 1997 {{ISBN|978-0-340-58431-6}} (verification and page number needed)</ref>\n\n==Examples of events==\nIn the Norwegian Arctic, Svalbard is an [[archipelago]] containing hundreds of glaciers. Svalbard is more than 60% covered by glaciers<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www3.hi.is/~oi/svalbard_geology.htm |title=Ing\u00f3lfsson, \u00d3lafur, ''Outline of the Physical Geography and Geology of Svalbard'' |publisher=.hi.is |date= |accessdate=2013-09-24}}</ref> and of these glaciers, hundreds have been observed to surge.<ref name=Dowdeswell/>\n\nGlacial surges in Karakoram occur in the presence of \"extreme uplift and denudation.\"<ref name=Dowdeswell/>\n\nIn 1980, there were several mini-surges of Variegated Glacier in Alaska. Mini surges typically show lag times of [[basal flow]] of 5\u201310 hours, which correlates to differences between the surging part of a glacier and the output of water and sediment.<ref name=Humphrey/> When the 1982 surge ended on July 5, there was a large flood event that day, and more flooding in the following days. What Humphrey found in his study is that behind the glacial surge zone, there are predominantly low basal water velocities, and high sliding rates before the rapid release of large quantities of water.<ref name=Humphrey>Humphrey, Neil Frank. Basal Hydrology of a Surge-Type Glacier: Observations and Theory Relating to Variegated Glacier. University of Washington, 1987</ref>\n\n==Causes==\nThere have been many theories of why glacial surges occur.\n\n===Hydrological control===\nSurges may be caused by the supply of meltwater to the base of a glacier. Meltwater is important in reducing frictional forces to glacial ice flow. The distribution and pressure of water at the bed modulates the glacier's velocity and therefore mass balance. Meltwater may come from a number of sources, including [[supraglacial lake]]s, geothermal heating of the bed, conduction of heat into the glacier and latent heat transfers. There is a positive feedback between velocity and friction at the bed, high velocities will generate more frictional heat and create more meltwater. [[crevasse|Crevassing]] is also enhanced by greater velocity flow which will provide further rapid transmission paths for meltwater flowing towards the bed. However, Humphrey found no precise correlation between ice-slow down and the release of water inside of a glacier.<ref name=Humphrey/>\n\nThe evolution of the drainage system under the glacier plays a key role in surge cycles.\n\n===Thermal regime===\n\nGlaciers that exhibit surges like those in Svalbard; with slower onset phase, and a longer termination phase may be thermally controlled rather than hydrologically controlled.<ref>Fowler, A. C., Murray, T. and Ng, F.S.L., ''Thermal regulation of glacier surging,'' Journal of Glaciology, 47(159), 527-538, 2001</ref><ref name=JJ/> These surges tend to last for longer periods of time than hydrologically controlled surges.\n\n===Deformable bed hypothesis===\nIn other cases, the [[geology]] of the underlying [[country rock (geology)|country rock]] may dictate surge frequency.{{Citation needed|date=November 2010}}  For example, poorly consolidated sedimentary rocks are more prone to failure under stress; a sub-glacial \"landslip\" may permit the glacier to slide.  This explains why surging glaciers tend to cluster{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}} in certain areas.\n\n===Critical mass===\n\nMeier and Post<ref>Meier, M.F. and Post, A.S., 1969, ''What are glacier surges?'' Canadian Journal of Earth Sciences 6, 807-817</ref> suggest that once mass accumulates to a critical point, basal melting begins to occur.  This provides a buoyancy force, \"lifting\" the glacier from the bed and reducing the friction force.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*[Dowdeswell,J.A., B. Unwin, A. -M. Nuttall and D. J. Wingham. 1999.  Velocity structure, flow instability and mass flux on a large Arctic ice cap from satellite radar interferometry. Elsevier Science B.V.]\n*[Humphrey, Neil Frank. Basal Hydrology of a Surge-Type Glacier: Observations and Theory Relating to Variegated Glacier. University of Washington, 1987.]\n* [Jiskoot H, DT Juhlin. 2009. Surge of a small East Greenland glacier, 2001\u20132007, suggests Svalbard-type surge mechanism. Journal of Glaciology, Vol. 55, No. 191., pp.&nbsp;567\u2013570.]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050323125548/http://users.aber.ac.uk/kak3/glacier_surges.htm https://web.archive.org/web/20050323125548/http://users.aber.ac.uk/kak3/glacier_surges.htm]\n* http://www.bgrg.org/pages/education/alevel/coldenvirons/Lesson%208.htm http://www.bgrg.org/pages/education/alevel/coldenvirons/Lesson%208.htm\n*[http://www3.hi.is/~oi/svalbard_geology.htm]\n* [Murray, T., T. Strozzi, A. Luckman, H. Jiskoot, and P. Christakos (2003), Is there a single surge mechanism? Contrasts in dynamics between glacier surges in Svalbard and other regions, J. Geophys. Res., 108(B5), 2237, ] {{doi|10.1029/2002JB001906}}.\n* [Fowler, A. C., Murray, T. and Ng, F.S.L. Thermal regulation of glacier surging. Journal of Glaciology, 47(159), 527\u2013538, 2001.]\n* Summerfield, Michael A. 1991. Global Geomorphology, an introduction to the study of landforms. Pearson, Prentice Hall. Harlow, England\n* [M Sharp. 1988. Surging glaciers: geomorphic effects. Progress in Physical geography. ppg.sagepub.com]\n* [http://ice.tsu.ru/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=189&Itemid=88 Stephen G. Evans, Olga V. Tutubalina, Valery N. Drobyshev, Sergey S. Chernomorets, Scott McDougall, Dmitry A. Petrakov, Oldrich Hungr. Catastrophic detachment and high-velocity long-runout flow of Kolka Glacier, Caucasus Mountains, Russia in 2002 // Geomorphology, 2009. - Vol. 105. - P. 314\u2013321.]\n{{glaciers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Surge (Glacier)}}\n[[Category:Glaciology]]\n", "text_old": "'''Glacial surges''' are short-lived events where a [[glacier]] can advance substantially, moving at velocities up to 100 times faster than normal.  Surging glaciers cluster around a few areas. High concentrations of surging glaciers occur in [[Svalbard]], the [[Canadian Arctic islands]], [[Alaska]] and [[Iceland]]. In some glaciers, surges can occur in fairly regular cycles, with 15 to 100 or more surge events per year. In other glaciers, surging remains unpredictable.<ref>Summerfield, Michael A., 1991, ''Global Geomorphology, an introduction to the study of landforms,'' Pearson, Prentice Hall. Harlow, England</ref> In some glaciers, however, the period of stagnation and build-up between two surges typically lasts 10 to 200 years and is called the quiescent phase.<ref name=Dowdeswell>\nDowdeswell, J. A., B. Unwin, A. M. Nuttall and D. J. Wingham. 1999. Velocity structure, flow instability and mass flux on a large Arctic ice cap from satellite radar interferometry. Elsevier Science B.V.\n</ref>\nDuring this period the velocities of the glacier are significantly lower, and the glaciers can [[glacier retreat|retreat]] substantially.\n\n==Types==\n\nGlacier surges have been divided into two categories depending on the character of the surge event. Glaciers in Alaska exhibit surges with a sudden onset, an extremely high maximum flow rate (tens of meters/day) and a sudden termination, often with a discharge of stored water. These are called Alaskan-type surges and it is suspected that these surges are hydrologically controlled.<ref>Sharp, M., 1988, ''Surging glaciers: geomorphic effects,'' Progress in Physical geography, http://ppg.sagepub.com</ref>\n\nSurges in Svalbard typically exhibit different behavior. Svalbard surges are typically associated with slower onset with an acceleration phase, rising to a maximum velocity which is typically slower (up to four or five meters per day) than Alaskan surges, and a return to quiescence often taking years.<ref name=JJ>Jiskoot, H. and D. T. Juhlin, 2009, ''Surge of a small East Greenland glacier, 2001\u20132007, suggests Svalbard-type surge mechanism,'' Journal of Glaciology, Vol. 55, No. 191, pp. 567\u2013570</ref><ref>Murray, T., T. Strozzi, A. Luckman, H. Jiskoot, and P. Christakos (2003), ''Is there a single surge mechanism? Contrasts in dynamics between glacier surges in Svalbard and other regions,'' J. Geophys. Res., 108(B5), 2237, {{doi|10.1029/2002JB001906}} </ref>  Features observed during the active or surge phase include [[pothole]]s, known as lacunas<ref>Post, A. 1969, ''Distribution of surging glaciers in western North America,'' J. Glaciol., 8(53), 229-240.</ref> and medial moraines.<ref>Benn, Douglas I. and David J. A. Evans, ''Glaciers and Glaciation,'' Hodder Arnold, 1997 {{ISBN|978-0-340-58431-6}} (verification and page number needed)</ref>\n\n==Examples of events==\nIn the Norwegian Arctic, Svalbard is an [[archipelago]] containing hundreds of glaciers. Svalbard is more than 60% covered by glaciers<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www3.hi.is/~oi/svalbard_geology.htm |title=Ing\u00f3lfsson, \u00d3lafur, ''Outline of the Physical Geography and Geology of Svalbard'' |publisher=.hi.is |date= |accessdate=2013-09-24}}</ref> and of these glaciers, hundreds have been observed to surge.<ref name=Dowdeswell/>\n\nGlacial surges in Karakoram occur in the presence of \"extreme uplift and denudation.\"<ref name=Dowdeswell/>\n\nIn 1980, there were several mini-surges of Variegated Glacier in Alaska. Mini surges typically show lag times of [[basal flow]] of 5\u201310 hours, which correlates to differences between the surging part of a glacier and the output of water and sediment.<ref name=Humphrey/> When the 1982 surge ended on July 5, there was a large flood event that day, and more flooding in the following days. What Humphrey found in his study is that behind the glacial surge zone, there are predominantly low basal water velocities, and high sliding rates before the rapid release of large quantities of water.<ref name=Humphrey>Humphrey, Neil Frank. Basal Hydrology of a Surge-Type Glacier: Observations and Theory Relating to Variegated Glacier. University of Washington, 1987</ref>\n\n==Causes==\nThere have been many theories of why glacial surges occur.\n\n===Hydrological control===\nSurges may be caused by the supply of meltwater to the base of a glacier. Meltwater is important in reducing frictional forces to glacial ice flow. The distribution and pressure of water at the bed modulates the glacier's velocity and therefore mass balance. Meltwater may come from a number of sources, including [[supraglacial lake]]s, geothermal heating of the bed, conduction of heat into the glacier and latent heat transfers. There is a positive feedback between velocity and friction at the bed, high velocities will generate more frictional heat and create more meltwater. [[crevasse|Crevassing]] is also enhanced by greater velocity flow which will provide further rapid transmission paths for meltwater flowing towards the bed. However, Humphrey found no precise correlation between ice-slow down and the release of water inside of a glacier.<ref name=Humphrey/>\n\nThe evolution of the drainage system under the glacier plays a key role in surge cycles.\n\n===Thermal regime===\n\nGlaciers that exhibit surges like those in Svalbard; with slower onset phase, and a longer termination phase may be thermally controlled rather than hydrologically controlled.<ref>Fowler, A. C., Murray, T. and Ng, F.S.L., ''Thermal regulation of glacier surging,'' Journal of Glaciology, 47(159), 527-538, 2001</ref><ref name=JJ/> These surges tend to last for longer periods of time than hydrologically controlled surges.\n\n===Deformable bed hypothesis===\nIn other cases, the [[geology]] of the underlying [[country rock (geology)|country rock]] may dictate surge frequency.{{Citation needed|date=November 2010}}  For example, poorly consolidated sedimentary rocks are more prone to failure under stress; a sub-glacial \"landslip\" may permit the glacier to slide.  This explains why surging glaciers tend to cluster{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}} in certain areas.\n\n===Critical mass===\n\nMeier and Post<ref>Meier, M.F. and Post, A.S., 1969, ''What are glacier surges?'' Canadian Journal of Earth Sciences 6, 807-817</ref> suggest that once mass accumulates to a critical point, basal melting begins to occur.  This provides a buoyancy force, \"lifting\" the glacier from the bed and reducing the friction force.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*[Dowdeswell,J.A., B. Unwin, A. -M. Nuttall and D. J. Wingham. 1999.  Velocity structure, flow instability and mass flux on a large Arctic ice cap from satellite radar interferometry. Elsevier Science B.V.]\n*[Humphrey, Neil Frank. Basal Hydrology of a Surge-Type Glacier: Observations and Theory Relating to Variegated Glacier. University of Washington, 1987.]\n* [Jiskoot H, DT Juhlin. 2009. Surge of a small East Greenland glacier, 2001\u20132007, suggests Svalbard-type surge mechanism. Journal of Glaciology, Vol. 55, No. 191., pp.&nbsp;567\u2013570.]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050323125548/http://users.aber.ac.uk/kak3/glacier_surges.htm https://web.archive.org/web/20050323125548/http://users.aber.ac.uk/kak3/glacier_surges.htm]\n* http://www.bgrg.org/pages/education/alevel/coldenvirons/Lesson%208.htm http://www.bgrg.org/pages/education/alevel/coldenvirons/Lesson%208.htm\n*[http://www3.hi.is/~oi/svalbard_geology.htm]\n* [Murray, T., T. Strozzi, A. Luckman, H. Jiskoot, and P. Christakos (2003), Is there a single surge mechanism? Contrasts in dynamics between glacier surges in Svalbard and other regions, J. Geophys. Res., 108(B5), 2237, ] {{doi|10.1029/2002JB001906}}.\n* [Fowler, A. C., Murray, T. and Ng, F.S.L. Thermal regulation of glacier surging. Journal of Glaciology, 47(159), 527-538, 2001.]\n* Summerfield, Michael A. 1991. Global Geomorphology, an introduction to the study of landforms. Pearson, Prentice Hall. Harlow, England\n* [M Sharp. 1988. Surging glaciers: geomorphic effects. Progress in Physical geography. ppg.sagepub.com]\n* [http://ice.tsu.ru/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=189&Itemid=88 Stephen G. Evans, Olga V. Tutubalina, Valery N. Drobyshev, Sergey S. Chernomorets, Scott McDougall, Dmitry A. Petrakov, Oldrich Hungr. Catastrophic detachment and high-velocity long-runout flow of Kolka Glacier, Caucasus Mountains, Russia in 2002 // Geomorphology, 2009. - Vol. 105. - P. 314\u2013321.]\n{{glaciers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Surge (Glacier)}}\n[[Category:Glaciology]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBibliography:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 527-538 \u2192 527\u2013538", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surge_(glacier)"}
{"title_page": "Defence Health Services (Namibia)", "text_new": "{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name = Defence Health Services\n| image = \n| caption = \n| dates = \n| country = [[Namibia]]\n| allegiance =\n| branch =\n| type = \n| role = \n| size = \n| command_structure = [[Namibia Defence Force]]\n| garrison = \n| garrison_label = \n| nickname = \n| colors = \n| colors_label = \n| march = \n| start_date = \n| engagements = \n| current_commander = [[Brigadier General]] Sophia Ndeitunga\n| current_commander_label = Chief of Staff\n| ceremonial_chief = \n| ceremonial_chief_label = <!-- Insignia -->\n}}\n\n\nThe '''Defence Health Service''' Directorate is the branch of the [[Namibian Defence Force]] responsible for medical facilities and the training and deployment of all medical personnel within the force. \n\nIt is a significant actor in the effort to control [[HIV/AIDS]] within the NDF.\n\n\n\n==Organisation==\nThe Directorate is Headquartered in Windhoek at the Ministry of Defence Headquarters. It is headed by the Chief of Staff who is normally a qualified Medical Officer,The Chief of Staff Holds the rank of Brigadier General. The roles of the directorate is to direct health policy, provide medical supply and the maintenance of health facilities and training and deployment of Medical personnel.\n\n====Mobile Military Health====\n*Mobile Field Hospital<ref>https://www.thenamibian.mobi/197902/archive-read/Mobile-field-hospital-set-up-at-airport</ref><ref>https://economist.com.na/9565/health/armed-forces-receive-field-hospital/</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=5&v=_-t4dgaB_TM&feature=emb_logo</ref>\n\n====Tertiary Military Health====\n* Grootfontein Military Hospital<ref>https://www.defenceweb.co.za/land/land-land/namibian-defence-force-to-build-new-military-hospital/</ref>\n* Peter Mueshihange Military Center\n\n====Military Health Training====\n* Medical Training Wing<ref>https://www.namibian.com.na/index.php?id=15483&page=archive-read</ref></